review_blob: This is a great copy of a Belgian. Its close, but its no cigar. Yeasty nose - check. Golden color - check. Lace - negative. Breast palate - check. Layers in the taste - negative.
beer_name: Left Coast Asylum Belgian-Style Tripel Ale

review_blob: Gift can that is product of a Smokey and the Banditesque beer run. Pale hazy yellow, no lasting head, little lace. Hops on nose. Sip is good, more hops than malt with plenty of each. Hops turn bitter fast. I get it, but this is more a case of demand or exclusivity prompting a higher rating.
Suitcase Of Cans - Basic budget brew, tastes better than most in that age bracket
22 oz - I get the idea. Its nothing Id seek out, but it compliments the basic roasted marshmallow undertone.
beer_name: Stone Imperial Russian Stout - Chai Spiced

review_blob: I like Guinness, and I like IPA. To me, that made ordering this a no-brainer. However, when you put two things together you dont always get better than the sum of their parts. Get a Guinness or get an IPA. Dont try to get both together.
12 oz - Frothy, fizzy mouthfeel, funky Belgian kick at the end. I can see this working.
12 oz bottle - I get it after reading the back label. Pale gold, light lace, no real nose. Palate reminds me of St Germain liqueur.
12 ounce bottle - Rock candy, raisins, bread on nose. Mouthfeel is good. Molasses in the middle. Needed something on the back end. Ill look forward to this next Christmas.

12 oz - First taste sensation was similar to a barleywine: creamy and boozy. Tan lace and red/brown liquid, vanilla from bourbon notes on nose. Cask rounded out the malt and substantial hops, yet the bitterness still showed through.
750 ml - Should have saved this for Christmas. Palate evokes Christmas for me, with the spice twists and turns. Nose is yeast bomb, with a slightly sour finish and merengue head.
12 oz - Good, solid beer, substantial but still light. Indistinguishable from others. Can see it work at a Sabres or Bills game. Terry Pegula made another good branding choice.
22 oz dated Oct 15 - This was really nice. Enough funk to feel the brett, not too crazy. Raspberry showed through. Nose was mild even as it warmed.
Sample at Halloween party - Tan head, glossy black liquid. Palate is Mexican sundae, vanilla then chocolate then peanuts
12 oz bottle (gift on Halloween) - Im not sure about this. It was like wine and beer mixed up.
12 oz bottle (gift) - Seltzer on the finish dominates the palate. Good work but little to remember.
12 oz can (gift) - The watermelon is there on the finish, good times on a hot day, delivers as described.
beer_name: 21st Amendment Hell or High Watermelon Wheat

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: 12 oz - Gift bottle from Chris. Boozy, roasted nose, cocoa colored wisp of a head. Good depth of notes on palate. Good but not elite.
beer_name: Leinenkugels Big Eddy Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: 12 oz gift from Stacy - Nice two stroke color, cocoa lace, many layers on the palate. However, stout it is not.
Gift from Stacy - Theres enough there to quality this as an ale while still being approachable.
375 ml - Delivers as advertised. Pear juice, funky yeast, wild acidity. All things that are good.
Tap at brewery - One of the best I found in the area. Big, bright nose with good color and lace. Malt takes over at the end.
Tap at brewery - Reasonable nose, not sure how this is an IPA. More malt than hops. Ok
Tap at brewery - Malt dominates, limited carbonation and head, no lace. Nice but forgettable.
beer_name: Lost Borough Park Ave Pale Ale

review_blob: 12 oz - Nice pour and lace, nose was spot on with malt and hops. Metallic funk in the middle killed it for me.
12 oz can - Hits the right notes. Good hops, good malt, delivers as promised as a session ale.
12 oz - Inviting nose of malt and mild hops. Robust flavor without overpowering. Delivered what was promised.
12 oz - Nice head, good lace. Hoppy punch over seltzer mouthfeel. More like a saison..
12 oz can (which are awesome) - Good malt, bright, lemony hops, solid carbonation. I like it.
750 ml - Yeasty golden goodness under puffy white head. Starts sweet then the hops crack back.
22 oz cellared - Nice and big and chewy. Layered wonderfulness of hop, malt, and spice.
22 oz cellared - Ive been sitting on this one. The time was right. Nice ale, gold color, froth. I really had no sense of the chiles or the cinnamon.
Sat on this for 5 years before cracking it open. Creamy first impression, drinks more like a quadruppel than anything else I can think of.

I can tell a lot of care and work went into this, but I still dont get it. Im not entirely sure what to think of this. Its kind of a once a year thing, like eating way too much before watching a whole bunch of football games. I guess it fits in so well for Thanksgiving. The rum barrel aging was a nice diversion.
beer_name: Southern Tier Rum Barrel Aged Pumking

review_blob: Draft - Watery, with little mouthfeel. Good carbonation. This really feels like a macro.
12 oz - Gift from PD. Normally not my cup of tea, I find barley wines out of balance, too much at once. Not that way here at all. Creamy goodness.
22 oz - Golden color, good lace. I dont get it. Whats new and different? Unremarkable.
12 oz - Bringing a rye to a porter turned out a lot better than expected. It matched with the transition to Winter very well.
Testing out different canned IPAs. I like this, but its no standout, especially in the crowded, competitive style
beer_name: 21st Amendment Brew Free or Die IPA

review_blob: I do appreciate the cans. Reminded me in a way of Lipton Iced Tea. Good but not worth seeking out.

2011 batch consumed 10 Aug 14 - Gift bottle from Eric K: Breakfast in the infield of Watkins Glen. Luscious, viscous pour, wisp of a head. The palate twists and turns befit the road course setting. Nothing Id change.
beer_name: Three Floyds Dark Lord Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: 330 ml - Gift bottle from Tausch. Nice skunky, stinky eurolager. Healthy carbonation.
12 oz - Roasted notes, busy, busy palate, really nice. Hops present, but didnt overshadow the stout.
12 oz - Came dangerously close to a drain pour. Way too sweet on first sip, became less shocking. Not for me
12 oz - Too mild for an IPA, and not funky enough to be seen as a Belgian. Good not great
12 oz - Nice IPA with underlying selzerlike carbonation and funk of a Belgian
12 oz - Light flavors without being flavorless. Solid carbonation without being fizzy.
750 ml - Good enough, decent head, vibrant orange, yeast and malt on palate
750 ml - Hit the marks required for the style, good to see a US brewer turning this out, stayed true to style
beer_name: Sierra Nevada / Russian River BRUX Domesticated Wild Ale

review_blob: Draft - Luminous orange with decent head of yellowish foam. Palate is good but doesnt have the strong backbone, but I think this is crafted well for Southern weather.
Gift bottle from PD - Luscious foam, hazy orange pour, vaguely waxy mouthfeel. Lots going on here, but it needed to be directed or pointed a little more.
beer_name: Rogue XS Imperial India Pale Ale (IPA)
